-- Migration 012c: Implementation Plans — Batch C (IDs 54-65)
-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
BEGIN;

-- ── ID 54: R&D Investment Escalation — Reaching 1.5% of GDP ──────────────────────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    54,
    'DSIT, National Treasury, and the Technology Innovation Agency (TIA) will implement a phased R&D investment escalation programme targeting 1.5% of GDP in GERD by 2030. The strategy has three pillars: (1) reform and expand the Section 11D R&D tax incentive to increase the effective subsidy rate for qualifying business R&D, removing the cap on deductible expenditure and broadening eligible activities to include software and process innovation; (2) double the Innovation Fund allocation from R1.5 billion to R3 billion per biennium, directing capital to deep-tech ventures in energy, health, and advanced manufacturing; and (3) increase competitive research grants via the NRF and MRC by 15% per year over five years. The National Research and Innovation Strategy (NRIS) 2030 provides the overarching framework. Success is measured by GERD reaching 0.9% of GDP by 2027 and 1.5% by 2030, with the private-sector share rising from 42% to 55%.',
    '[
      {"step":1,"description":"DSIT commissions an independent review of the Section 11D tax incentive regime — expenditure caps, qualifying activities, and administrative burden — benchmarked against OECD best practice (UK R&D credits, Australia R&D Tax Incentive); review to be completed within 6 months and submitted to National Treasury for Budget 2026 consideration","timeline":"Q2–Q4 2025","responsible_party":"DSIT / National Treasury / SARS"},
      {"step":2,"description":"National Treasury publishes a draft amendment to the Income Tax Act expanding Section 11D: remove the R150 million cap on qualifying R&D expenditure for large firms, extend eligible activities to software R&D and process innovation, and increase the deduction rate from 150% to 175% for qualifying SMMEs; gazette for public comment through SARS","timeline":"Q1 2026 (Budget 2026 announcement)","responsible_party":"National Treasury / SARS / DSIT"},
      {"step":3,"description":"TIA and Innovation Fund scale the deep-tech venture funding programme: establish a R3 billion biennial allocation with ring-fenced sub-funds for green hydrogen, advanced manufacturing, health technology, and agri-tech; appoint fund managers through a competitive process overseen by DSIT; publish annual portfolio performance reports","timeline":"Q2 2026–Q4 2027","responsible_party":"DSIT / TIA / Innovation Fund"},
      {"step":4,"description":"NRF and MRC competitive grant allocations: DSIT secures a 15% per-year increase in NRF and MRC grant budgets over five years (2026–2030); introduce a new Industry-Academia Co-funding Grant (matched 50:50 with private sector) with a minimum R500 million per year allocation; require all funded research to disclose commercialisation pathways","timeline":"Annual from Q1 2026","responsible_party":"NRF / MRC / DSIT"},
      {"step":5,"description":"Establish a GERD Monitoring and Reporting Framework: annual GERD survey by Stats SA (aligned to Frascati Manual) disaggregated by sector, source of funds, and province; publish GERD data annually; report progress against 1.5% NDP target to the Inter-Ministerial Committee on Science, Technology and Innovation","timeline":"Annual from Q4 2026","responsible_party":"Stats SA / DSIT"},
      {"step":6,"description":"DSIT convenes an Annual National R&D Investment Summit with industry (BUSA, NAAMSA, Pharmaceuticals SA), universities (USAf), and science councils (CSIR, SAIMR) to align private R&D pipeline commitments and identify binding administrative constraints; publish an industry R&D investment pledge register","timeline":"Annual from Q3 2026","responsible_party":"DSIT / BUSA / USAf"}
    ]',
    '2025–2030; Section 11D reform in Budget 2026; GERD 0.9% by 2027; GERD 1.5% by 2030',
    'Section 11D expanded incentive: estimated R4–6 billion per year in additional revenue foregone (National Treasury modelling); Innovation Fund doubling: additional R1.5 billion per biennium (DSIT budget); NRF/MRC grant increases: R2 billion additional over 5 years; total incremental public cost: R15–18 billion over 2026–2030',
    'Income Tax Act 58 of 1962 (Section 11D amendment); South African Revenue Service Act 34 of 1997 (administrative procedures); Technology Innovation Agency Act 26 of 2008 (potential capitalisation increase); National Research Foundation Act 23 of 1998',
    'Section 11D amendment: National Treasury prepares a Taxation Laws Amendment Bill for introduction to Parliament annually in July–August after Budget. Expanding eligibility and deduction rates is a clause-level amendment with no constitutional issues. The TIA capitalisation increase requires a DSIT appropriation amendment — straightforward if supported by National Treasury. The Industry-Academia Co-funding Grant requires no new legislation; it is administered as a conditional grant framework under the PFMA.',
    'Moderate-to-strong feasibility within the GNU. DSIT (ANC) and the DA both publicly support reaching the NDP R&D target. National Treasury is supportive of the tax incentive reform in principle but will resist large revenue foregone estimates without robust evaluation evidence. The private sector (BUSA) has lobbied for Section 11D reform for a decade. Key risk is the pace of private-sector response — South Africa''s corporate R&D culture is historically weak outside mining and pharmaceuticals.',
    'South Korea''s GERD trajectory from 0.6% (1980) to 4.9% of GDP (2022) demonstrates the long-term payoff of sustained public R&D investment paired with aggressive tax incentives. Israel''s Office of the Chief Scientist (now Israel Innovation Authority) used matched-funding grants to build a globally leading tech sector from a small base — directly analogous to SA''s TIA-Innovation Fund model. Australia''s R&D Tax Incentive (43.5% refundable credit for SMEs) reduced administrative burden and increased business R&D by 18% in the first three years after the 2011 reform.'
);

-- ── ID 55: NSFAS Fraud Prevention and Administration System Overhaul ──────────────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    55,
    'The DHET, NSFAS Board, and the Presidential Task Team will implement a comprehensive administration overhaul addressing the R14 billion in overpayments, ghost student fraud, and the collapse of the student accommodation operator system. The reform has three tracks: (1) a Digital Verification Gateway linking NSFAS eligibility assessments to Home Affairs (DHA), SARS, and institution student information systems in real time; (2) a direct payment system replacing Student Accommodation Operators (SAOs) and their documented history of fund diversion; and (3) governance restructuring of the NSFAS Board and management, including a ring-fenced forensic investigation unit. The target is reducing system leakage to below 1% of total disbursements by 2027 and processing all applications within 30 days of registration confirmation.',
    '[
      {"step":1,"description":"DHET and NSFAS appoint a suitably qualified Administrator (or confirm permanent CEO) with a clear mandate to implement the Presidential Task Team recommendations within 18 months; establish a dedicated NSFAS Turnaround PMO with weekly reporting to the Minister and the Portfolio Committee on Higher Education","timeline":"Q1 2025 (immediate)","responsible_party":"DHET / NSFAS Board / Presidency"},
      {"step":2,"description":"Deploy the Digital Verification Gateway: integrate NSFAS eligibility verification with DHA HANIS biometric database, SARS income verification API, and HEMIS (DHET''s Higher Education Management Information System) for real-time student enrolment confirmation; pilot at 5 large institutions before national rollout; conduct parallel verification of all 1.3 million active beneficiaries against DHA and SARS records to identify ghost students","timeline":"Q2–Q4 2025","responsible_party":"NSFAS / DHA / SARS / DHET"},
      {"step":3,"description":"Implement direct payment to students: establish a NSFAS Digital Wallet (ring-fenced bank account linked to student ID) in partnership with a major bank; phase out all SAO intermediary payments for accommodation; require institutions to register private accommodation providers through a national registry with annual financial audits; complete transition by end-2025","timeline":"Q2 2025–Q1 2026","responsible_party":"NSFAS / DHET / National Treasury / Banking sector"},
      {"step":4,"description":"Establish the NSFAS Forensic Investigation Unit: appoint SIU (Special Investigating Unit) under Presidential Proclamation to investigate all identified ghost student cases and SAO fraud; refer cases for criminal prosecution through the NPA; recover overpayments through civil and criminal proceedings; publish quarterly recovery progress reports","timeline":"Q2 2025–Q4 2026","responsible_party":"SIU / NPA / NSFAS"},
      {"step":5,"description":"NSFAS Board governance reform: amend the Higher Education Act to align NSFAS Board composition with PFMA Schedule 3 requirements; require Board members to hold relevant financial management qualifications; limit Board tenure to two terms; introduce mandatory Declaration of Interests register with public disclosure; appoint an independent Audit and Risk Committee","timeline":"Q3 2025–Q2 2026","responsible_party":"DHET / NSFAS Board / Parliament"},
      {"step":6,"description":"Annual performance audit: the Auditor-General and an independent student support organisation (NSFAS Student Reference Group) co-publish an annual NSFAS performance assessment covering disbursement accuracy, application turnaround times, accommodation quality, and student satisfaction; table in Parliament and publish on NSFAS website","timeline":"Annual from Q4 2026","responsible_party":"Auditor-General / DHET / NSFAS"}
    ]',
    '18-month intensive turnaround (2025–2026); Digital Verification Gateway live Q4 2025; direct payment system operational Q1 2026; ongoing forensic recovery 2025–2027',
    'Digital Verification Gateway implementation: R120–180 million (ICT procurement, DHA and SARS API integration); Direct Payment Digital Wallet infrastructure: R80–120 million; SIU forensic investigation: R40–60 million (Presidential Proclamation budget); total turnaround investment: R300–400 million — recoverable against projected fraud reduction savings of R2–3 billion per year',
    'Higher Education Act 101 of 1997 (NSFAS provisions, Section 50 Board composition amendment); Public Finance Management Act 1 of 1999 (Schedule 3 governance requirements); Prevention and Combating of Corrupt Activities Act 12 of 2004; Special Investigating Units and Special Tribunals Act 74 of 1996 (Presidential Proclamation for SIU mandate)',
    'DHET can instruct NSFAS as a Schedule 3A public entity under the PFMA without primary legislation for most operational reforms. Board composition changes require an amendment to the Higher Education Act — achievable via a short amendment bill. The SIU investigation requires a Presidential Proclamation (statutory instrument, not legislation). DHA data-sharing requires a formal MoU between NSFAS and DHA under POPIA framework.',
    'Strong cross-party and public demand for NSFAS reform following the 2022–2023 scandal. DHET Minister has publicly committed to implementing all Presidential Task Team recommendations. The DA and EFF have tabled parliamentary questions and motions, creating political pressure for visible progress. Risk: institutional resistance within NSFAS and the SAO industry; student protests around payment disruptions during the transition. The GNU''s credibility is partly tied to visible anti-corruption delivery.',
    'Australia''s HECS-HELP student loan system uses ATO (tax authority) real-time income verification to determine repayment obligations — a direct model for SA''s DHA-SARS verification gateway. The UK''s Student Loans Company implemented a digital fraud detection system in 2019 using HMRC income data linkage, reducing fraudulent claims by 34% in the first year. Ghana''s GETFUND (Ghana Education Trust Fund) implemented biometric student verification in 2021 following documented ghost student fraud.'
);

-- ── ID 56: Post-School Education Pathways — CET and Second-Chance Programme ──────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    56,
    'DHET will develop a structured Post-School Education and Training (PSET) articulation framework linking SA''s 50 Community Education and Training (CET) colleges, 50 TVET colleges, and the university sector into coherent pathways for the estimated 11 million NEETs. The framework requires three interlocking reforms: (1) CET college recapitalisation with dedicated infrastructure funding and qualified lecturer capacity; (2) NQF articulation agreements enabling CET students to progress to TVET Levels 2–4 with credit recognition; and (3) Second Chance Matric Programme scaling to process 200,000+ candidates per cycle with expanded subject-specific support. SAQA will coordinate the NQF qualification alignment. The QCTO will develop new occupational qualifications in artisan and digital economy pathways accessible through CET entry points. Success is measured by 500,000 NEET learners enrolled in PSET pathways by 2028 with 60% completion rates.',
    '[
      {"step":1,"description":"DHET publishes a PSET Pathways White Paper consolidating CET, TVET, and Second Chance policy into a single articulation framework; define progression routes from CET (NQF Level 1) through TVET (Levels 2–5) to occupational qualifications; gazette for public comment and table in Parliament for Portfolio Committee adoption","timeline":"Q2–Q4 2025","responsible_party":"DHET / SAQA / QCTO"},
      {"step":2,"description":"CET college recapitalisation: DHET secures a dedicated CET infrastructure budget of R500 million per year; prioritise fibre connectivity, computer labs, and workshop facilities at the 50 CET colleges; establish minimum staffing norms (1 qualified lecturer per 25 learners) and fund bursaries for 2,000 CET lecturer posts over 3 years through ETDP SETA","timeline":"Q1 2026–Q4 2028","responsible_party":"DHET / ETDP SETA / National Treasury"},
      {"step":3,"description":"NQF articulation implementation: SAQA, QCTO, and UMALUSI develop formal credit accumulation and transfer (CAT) agreements enabling CET programme credits to count towards TVET qualification requirements; pilot at 10 CET-TVET linked campuses; require all TVET colleges to publish articulation pathways for each programme by end-2026","timeline":"Q2 2025–Q4 2026","responsible_party":"SAQA / QCTO / UMALUSI / DHET"},
      {"step":4,"description":"Second Chance Matric Programme scaling: increase examination centres from 580 to 800; expand the online subject preparation platform (currently 14 subjects) to full CAPS curriculum; establish 50 walk-in support centres co-located with CET colleges; provide bursaries for 50,000 candidates per year from NSFAS Second Chance allocation","timeline":"Q1 2026–Q4 2027","responsible_party":"DHET / DBE / Umalusi / NSFAS"},
      {"step":5,"description":"QCTO occupational qualification development for CET entry pathways: develop and register 20 new occupational qualifications at NQF Level 2–3 in priority areas — solar PV installation, early childhood development, community health work, and digital literacy — accessible to learners with Grade 9 or CET Level 1 entry; engage EWSETA, CHIETA, and HWSETA for SLA-funded practical components","timeline":"Q3 2025–Q4 2026","responsible_party":"QCTO / Sector Education and Training Authorities / DHET"},
      {"step":6,"description":"NEET tracking and labour market linkage: Stats SA and DHET establish a NEET register using SARS, UIF, and Home Affairs data to track 11 million NEETs and measure enrolment, qualification attainment, and employment outcomes; publish annual NEET report; link performance to CET and TVET college conditional grant allocations","timeline":"Annual from Q4 2026","responsible_party":"Stats SA / DHET / SARS / DHA"}
    ]',
    '2025 White Paper; 2026–2028 implementation; 500,000 NEET enrolments by 2028; full articulation framework operational by 2027',
    'CET recapitalisation: R500 million per year additional (DHET budget); TVET infrastructure and staffing: R1.2 billion per year (existing + increase); Second Chance scaling: R300 million per year; QCTO qualification development: R80 million; total additional annual cost: R2 billion above current PSET baselines — partially offsettable through SETA discretionary grant reallocation',
    'Further Education and Training Act 16 of 2006 (CET college mandate); South African Qualifications Authority Act 58 of 1995 (NQF articulation framework); National Qualifications Framework Act 67 of 2008; Higher Education Act 101 of 1997 (NSFAS Second Chance provisions)',
    'The PSET White Paper is a policy instrument, not primary legislation. NQF articulation agreements are issued by SAQA under the NQF Act without parliamentary process. CET college budget increases require MTEF allocation — National Treasury approval. QCTO occupational qualification registration is an administrative process under the NQF Act. Any changes to the Further Education and Training Act to strengthen CET governance would require a standard amendment bill.',
    'Moderate feasibility. DHET has strong political will. ANC education policy and the EFF both support PSET expansion. The fiscal constraint is the binding risk — CET colleges are severely underfunded and National Treasury has not ring-fenced a CET infrastructure allocation in recent MTEFs. The SETA reallocation mechanism (redirecting mandatory grant levies) faces SETA board resistance. International donor support (EU, GIZ) is available for programme design.',
    'Germany''s dual vocational training system, adapted through its development partnership with DHET through GIZ, provides the model for structured CET-TVET articulation. Brazil''s PROEJA programme integrated adult basic education with technical vocational training at SENAI and SENAC institutions, reaching 200,000 NEETs per year — directly comparable to SA''s scale challenge. Ireland''s Further Education and Training Authority (SOLAS) framework created clear progression pathways from community education to higher education, reducing NEET rates by 8 percentage points over a decade.'
);

-- ── ID 57: Advanced Manufacturing Skills for the Energy Transition ────────────────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    57,
    'DHET, merSETA, and CHIETA will lead a Green Skills Programme targeting 150,000 trained workers in EV battery technology, solar PV installation and maintenance, and green hydrogen production by 2030. The programme operates through three channels: (1) new QCTO occupational qualifications for each target trade, registered on the NQF at Levels 3–5; (2) industry-led apprenticeship programmes under merSETA and CHIETA with BMW, Volkswagen, Toyota, Scatec, Enertrag, and HDF Energy as anchor industry partners; and (3) conversion training for existing artisans in ICE automotive, electrical, and petrochemical sectors. The DTIC''s Green Economy Accreditation Centre will certify training providers. The Presidency''s Operation Vulindlela tracks energy skills as a reform enabler. A Just Transition financing window (managed by DBSA) will fund training for workers displaced from coal-related industries.',
    '[
      {"step":1,"description":"QCTO develops and registers new occupational qualifications: EV Battery Systems Technician (NQF Level 4), Solar PV Systems Installer and Maintainer (NQF Level 3), Green Hydrogen Production Operator (NQF Level 5); engage merSETA and CHIETA for workplace learning component design; set qualification registration deadline of Q4 2025","timeline":"Q2–Q4 2025","responsible_party":"QCTO / merSETA / CHIETA / DHET"},
      {"step":2,"description":"Establish the Green Skills Industry Apprenticeship Programme: merSETA and CHIETA issue calls for employer levy-grant agreements with BMW, Volkswagen, Toyota (EV); Scatec, Enertrag, Enel Green Power (solar); and Sasol, HDF Energy, Bosch (hydrogen); target 5,000 registered apprentices per year by 2027; DTIC co-funds with R200 million incentive budget","timeline":"Q1 2026–Q4 2027","responsible_party":"merSETA / CHIETA / DTIC / Industry partners"},
      {"step":3,"description":"Conversion training programme for displaced workers: identify 50,000 ICE automotive artisans (NUMSA/merSETA register), electrical workers (EWSETA), and petrochemical workers (CHIETA) eligible for upskilling; develop 3–6 month bridging qualifications with Recognition of Prior Learning (RPL) pathways; fund through the Just Transition financing window at DBSA","timeline":"Q2 2026–Q4 2028","responsible_party":"DBSA / merSETA / EWSETA / CHIETA / DHET"},
      {"step":4,"description":"TVET college green skills capacity-building: identify 20 TVET colleges in proximity to renewable energy zones (Northern Cape, Eastern Cape, KwaZulu-Natal) and EV manufacturing clusters (Eastern Cape, Gauteng); equip with solar PV workshop infrastructure and EV training vehicles; train 400 TVET lecturers in green technology systems through a master trainer programme","timeline":"Q1 2026–Q4 2027","responsible_party":"DHET / TVET colleges / EWSETA / merSETA"},
      {"step":5,"description":"Green Economy Accreditation Centre (GEAC): DTIC establishes GEAC as a specialised accreditation body for green skills training providers; publish minimum infrastructure standards for solar, EV, and hydrogen training facilities; conduct annual compliance audits; accreditation required for SETA levy-grant reimbursement eligibility","timeline":"Q3 2025–Q2 2026","responsible_party":"DTIC / QCTO / SANAS"},
      {"step":6,"description":"Skills pipeline monitoring: DSIT and DHET publish a quarterly Green Skills Dashboard tracking registered learners, qualification completions, employment placement rates, and employer satisfaction scores; report annually to the Presidential Climate Commission and the Portfolio Committee on Higher Education","timeline":"Quarterly from Q1 2026","responsible_party":"DSIT / DHET / Stats SA / Presidential Climate Commission"},
      {"step":7,"description":"International partnerships: DHET negotiates bilateral skills exchange agreements with Germany (BMBF), Denmark (Danish Energy Agency), and South Korea (KISA) for curriculum sharing, master trainer exchange, and TVET lecturer development in EV and hydrogen technologies; leverage GIZ''s existing SA vocational training partnership","timeline":"Q2 2025–Q4 2026","responsible_party":"DHET / DIRCO / GIZ"}
    ]',
    '2025–2030; QCTO qualifications registered Q4 2025; first apprenticeship cohort Q1 2026; 150,000 trained workers by 2030',
    'SETA mandatory grant reallocation: R1.5 billion over 5 years (from existing SETA levies); DTIC incentive budget: R200 million; TVET infrastructure: R600 million (20 colleges); DBSA Just Transition window: R2 billion; international development finance (GIZ, EU): R500 million; total programme cost: R4.8 billion over 5 years',
    'Skills Development Act 97 of 1998 (SETA mandate and levy-grant system); Skills Development Levies Act 9 of 1999; National Qualifications Framework Act 67 of 2008 (QCTO occupational qualification registration); Electricity Regulation Act 4 of 2006 (licensing of green energy training facilities)',
    'QCTO qualification registration is an administrative process requiring no legislation. SETA levy-grant reallocation for green skills requires merSETA and CHIETA Board resolutions — no legislative change. DTIC incentive programme operates under existing DTIC appropriation. DBSA Just Transition financing window is established by DBSA Board resolution under the Development Bank of Southern Africa Act. No new primary legislation required for the core programme.',
    'Strong feasibility. The Presidency''s Operation Vulindlela identifies skills for the energy transition as a priority. The Presidential Climate Commission (PCC) has published green skills estimates. merSETA and CHIETA have strong industrial relationships. BMW and VW have publicly committed to EV manufacturing investment conditional on skills availability. Union risk: NUMSA has raised concerns about ICE job displacement — the conversion training component is designed as a Just Transition concession. Political consensus within the GNU is strong on this issue.',
    'Germany''s Qualifizierungschancengesetz (Qualification Opportunities Act, 2019) provided conversion training funding for automotive workers transitioning from ICE to EV platforms — 200,000 workers enrolled in the first two years. Denmark''s energy technology vocational programme (Erhvervsuddannelse for energianlæg) created a structured pathway from secondary school to certified wind and solar technician in 3.5 years, supplying 8,000 new technicians per year. California''s SB 100 implementation included a $600 million green workforce training fund administered through community colleges — a model for SA''s TVET college green skills infrastructure investment.'
);

-- ── ID 58: Eskom Restructuring — Generation, Transmission, and Distribution ─────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    58,
    'The DMRE and National Treasury are implementing Eskom''s statutory unbundling into three entities: Eskom Generation Company (EGC), the National Transmission Company South Africa (NTCSA), and a reformed Electricity Distribution Industry (EDI). NTCSA was incorporated as a wholly state-owned subsidiary in 2024 and requires full capitalisation and a regulatory licence from NERSA. EGC remains within Eskom Holdings as the generation subsidiary. The EDI restructuring — transferring distribution assets to municipalities — is the most politically contested element and will require careful phasing. The Electricity Regulation Amendment Act (ERA Amendment, 2024) provides the legal basis for competitive electricity markets and multi-licencing. The Presidency''s Operation Vulindlela tracks unbundling milestones monthly. Success is defined as NTCSA operational as an independent entity with its own NERSA licence by Q4 2025, and the competitive generation market framework published by Q2 2026.',
    '[
      {"step":1,"description":"NTCSA full legal separation and capitalisation: NTCSA receives formal NERSA transmission licence (applied for Q1 2025); National Treasury and DBSA finalise the R100 billion 5-year capital plan for grid expansion; NTCSA appoints permanent executive team; first NTCSA Annual Transmission Development Plan published and gazetted for public comment","timeline":"Q2–Q4 2025","responsible_party":"DMRE / National Treasury / NTCSA / NERSA"},
      {"step":2,"description":"EGC governance and regulatory framework: Eskom Holdings hive down generation assets to EGC subsidiary; EGC applies for a generation licence from NERSA; establish an independent EGC Board with technical and financial expertise; National Treasury and Eskom agree on EGC performance milestones under the R254 billion debt relief conditions (see separate plan for ID 61)","timeline":"Q1–Q3 2026","responsible_party":"DMRE / Eskom Holdings / NERSA / National Treasury"},
      {"step":3,"description":"Competitive electricity market framework: NERSA publishes draft Market Rules for the competitive multi-buyer, multi-seller electricity market under the ERA Amendment Act; include provisions for open-access transmission, NTCSA as market operator, and competitive procurement rules for EGC and independent power producers; gazette for public comment with 60-day comment period","timeline":"Q2–Q4 2026","responsible_party":"NERSA / DMRE / NTCSA"},
      {"step":4,"description":"EDI restructuring phased plan: DMRE publishes a phased Distribution Sector Reform Roadmap; Phase 1 (2026–2028) strengthens metropolitan municipalities (eThekwini, City of Cape Town, Ekurhuleni) as viable distribution entities with ring-fenced distribution accounts and NERSA distribution licences; Phase 2 (2028–2030) addresses non-viable municipalities through a national distribution company or regional utility model","timeline":"Q3 2026–Q4 2030","responsible_party":"DMRE / COGTA / SALGA / Eskom Distribution"},
      {"step":5,"description":"Operation Vulindlela quarterly review mechanism: the Presidency''s Investment and Infrastructure Office (PIIO) publishes quarterly Eskom Restructuring Progress Reports with RAG status on NTCSA licensing, EGC hive-down, market rules publication, and EDI reform milestones; submit to Cabinet''s Economic Cluster and Portfolio Committee on Mineral Resources and Energy","timeline":"Quarterly from Q1 2025","responsible_party":"Presidency (PIIO) / DMRE / National Treasury"},
      {"step":6,"description":"Labour transition framework: engage NUM, NUMSA, and AMCU through Nedlac on the employment implications of unbundling; establish a joint labour-management task team for each entity (NTCSA, EGC, EDI); agree on ring-fenced retrenchment protections and skills conversion support funded through the Eskom Just Transition facility","timeline":"Q2 2025–Q2 2026","responsible_party":"DMRE / Eskom / Nedlac / NUM / NUMSA"}
    ]',
    'NTCSA licensing Q4 2025; EGC hive-down Q3 2026; competitive market rules Q4 2026; EDI reform 2026–2030',
    'NTCSA capitalisation: R100 billion over 5 years (World Bank, DBSA, NDB, with government guarantee); EGC legal hive-down: R50–80 million in legal and transaction costs; Market Rules development: R30 million (NERSA regulatory capacity); EDI restructuring: cost-neutral in aggregate but requires R5–10 billion for municipal distribution asset rehabilitation',
    'Electricity Regulation Amendment Act (2024) — primary enabling legislation for competitive market; Companies Act 71 of 2008 (subsidiary company structures for EGC and NTCSA); Local Government: Municipal Finance Management Act 56 of 2003 (EDI municipal distribution governance); Public Finance Management Act 1 of 1999 (Eskom schedule amendment)',
    'ERA Amendment Act (2024) has been enacted, providing the primary legal framework. NTCSA incorporation as a subsidiary company requires an Eskom Board resolution and DMRE ministerial determination — no parliamentary vote. The EGC hive-down is an internal corporate restructuring under the Companies Act. EDI reform affecting municipal licences requires NERSA licence transfers — administrative process under the ERA. A constitutional issue (Section 156 municipal competence over electricity distribution) may require a Constitutional Amendment Bill for Phase 2 EDI reforms involving full municipalisation.',
    'Moderate feasibility for NTCSA and EGC elements; low-to-moderate for EDI. Operation Vulindlela has political backing from the Presidency. National Treasury and the DA support full unbundling. ANC''s internal coal and municipal distribution interests create friction on EGC coal fleet decisions and EDI transfers. SALGA opposes a national distribution company model. Labour unions have accepted unbundling in principle but will resist operational headcount reductions. The GNU''s energy reform credibility depends on visible progress.',
    'Brazil''s Eletrobras restructuring (completed 2022) separated transmission (ONS) from generation and distribution through a capital markets privatisation model — the most comparable large utility unbundling. UK''s National Grid separation from British Gas (1986–1997) provides the canonical transmission-as-regulated-natural-monopoly model SA''s NTCSA is modelled on. India''s Electricity Act 2003 unbundled state electricity boards into separate GENCOs, TRANSCOs, and DISCOMs — with mixed results but instructive lessons for SA''s EDI municipal challenge.'
);

-- ── ID 59: Transnet Freight Rail and Port Private Sector Participation ────────────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    59,
    'Operation Vulindlela, the DTIC, and the Department of Public Enterprises (now DPEM) will implement Transnet''s Third-Party Access (TPA) programme on freight rail corridors and the private concessioning of container terminal operations at Durban and Cape Town ports. Transnet''s freight rail decline — from 230 million tonnes (2013) to under 155 million tonnes (2024) — represents a structural competitiveness failure costing exporters an estimated R50 billion per year. The reform programme has three pillars: (1) issuing TPA regulations to allow private operators on the coal (Richards Bay Coal Terminal) and iron ore (Sishen-Saldanha) export corridors and the general freight network; (2) concessioning Durban and Cape Town container terminals to private operators through a competitive bid process; and (3) restructuring Transnet into separate freight rail and port entities with independent boards and regulatory oversight by the Ports Regulator and a new Rail Regulator.',
    '[
      {"step":1,"description":"Third-Party Access regulations: DMRE and DTIC publish final TPA Framework under the National Rail Policy (2022) enabling private operators to access the Transnet freight rail network on regulated open-access terms; PRASA and Transnet Freight Rail to maintain separate track access charging frameworks; gazette and implement within 12 months","timeline":"Q2–Q4 2025","responsible_party":"DTIC / DMRE / Transnet / Presidency (PIIO)"},
      {"step":2,"description":"Pilot private operations on coal and iron ore corridors: issue Request for Qualification (RFQ) for private train operators on the Richards Bay Coal Terminal corridor (180km) and Sishen-Saldanha iron ore corridor (861km); award 10-year operating licences through a competitive bid; set performance targets of 90 million tonnes per year on coal corridor and 60 million tonnes on iron ore corridor by 2028","timeline":"Q1–Q4 2026","responsible_party":"Transnet Freight Rail / DTIC / Ports Regulator"},
      {"step":3,"description":"Container terminal concessions: DTIC and Transnet Port Terminals publish an Expression of Interest for private concessionaires at Durban Container Terminal (DCT, largest in Africa) and Cape Town Container Terminal; appoint transaction advisors; complete competitive bid process and award 25-year concession agreements with performance bonds and productivity targets (DCT: 3.5 million TEU/year by 2030)","timeline":"Q2 2025–Q4 2027","responsible_party":"DTIC / Transnet Port Terminals / Ports Regulator"},
      {"step":4,"description":"Transnet corporate restructuring: separate Transnet into three legally distinct subsidiaries — Transnet Freight Rail (TFR), Transnet Port Terminals (TPT), and Transnet National Ports Authority (TNPA); each entity to have an independent Board and CEO; establish TFR as a track-owning infrastructure manager and TPT as a port terminal operator eligible for partial private participation; gazette restructuring plan","timeline":"Q3 2026–Q2 2028","responsible_party":"DPEM / Transnet Holdings Board / DTIC"},
      {"step":5,"description":"Ports Regulator and Rail Regulator strengthening: increase Ports Regulator capacity and mandate to adjudicate terminal efficiency disputes, approve tariff applications, and publish annual port performance benchmarks; establish a dedicated Rail Economic Regulator (RER) under the National Rail Policy to regulate TPA charges, operator disputes, and infrastructure investment obligations","timeline":"Q1 2026–Q4 2027","responsible_party":"DTIC / Ports Regulator / DMRE"},
      {"step":6,"description":"Transnet balance sheet and operations recovery: National Treasury and DPEM agree on a Transnet debt restructuring facility (Transnet''s debt exceeded R130 billion in 2024); condition relief on operational milestone achievement — freight volumes, port turnaround times, locomotive fleet availability; appoint a Chief Restructuring Officer within Transnet Holdings","timeline":"Q1 2025–Q4 2026","responsible_party":"National Treasury / DPEM / Transnet"},
      {"step":7,"description":"Quarterly Transnet Scorecard: Operation Vulindlela PIIO publishes quarterly performance data on freight volumes (tonnes), port dwell times (days), locomotive availability (%), and TPA operator licences issued; report to Cabinet Economic Cluster and Portfolio Committee on Public Enterprises","timeline":"Quarterly from Q2 2025","responsible_party":"Presidency (PIIO) / Transnet / DTIC"}
    ]',
    'TPA regulations Q4 2025; corridor pilot licences Q4 2026; DCT concession Q4 2027; Transnet restructuring 2026–2028',
    'Transaction advisory costs for terminal concessions: R150–200 million; Rail Regulator establishment: R80 million; Transnet debt restructuring: contingent liability of R30–50 billion (government guarantee or direct relief to be determined by National Treasury); private concessionaire investment commitments expected to deliver R15–25 billion in terminal infrastructure',
    'National Ports Act 12 of 2005 (Ports Authority mandate, terminal concession framework); Legal Succession to the South African Transport Services Act 9 of 1989 (Transnet mandate); National Rail Policy 2022 (TPA framework basis); Companies Act 71 of 2008 (subsidiary restructuring)',
    'TPA Framework is published under existing DTIC and transport regulatory authority — no new primary legislation required. Port terminal concessions are authorised under the National Ports Act (Section 56 concessioning) — Transnet National Ports Authority Board resolution required. Transnet corporate restructuring into subsidiaries is a Companies Act process. Establishment of a Rail Economic Regulator as a stand-alone entity requires either an amendment to the Legal Succession Act or a new National Rail Bill.',
    'Moderate-to-strong feasibility. Operation Vulindlela has elevated Transnet reform to Cabinet priority with presidential support. DTIC and National Treasury are aligned. Key risk is Transnet management and labour (SATAWU, UNTU) resistance to private operators — managed through Nedlac consultation. The DA and IFP support rapid privatisation; ANC''s industrial policy wing supports state-led reform with private participation rather than full privatisation. Urgency is reinforced by mineral export revenue losses.',
    'Australia''s QR National (now Aurizon) privatisation of Queensland freight rail (2010) created the world''s largest coal haulage company and improved coal corridor throughput by 25% within five years. Dubai''s DP World Port concessioning model — implemented across 82 marine terminals globally — is the benchmark SA''s DCT concession is modelled on. Brazil''s Rumo Logística (formerly ALL) private freight rail operator achieved 25% volume growth on previously Governo-operated corridors within 3 years of the 1997 concession award.'
);

-- ── ID 60: SOE Policy Impediments Reform — PFMA, BBBEE, and Procurement ──────────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    60,
    'National Treasury and DPEM will develop an SOE-specific procurement framework that resolves the tension between PFMA governance requirements, B-BBEE compliance obligations, and the operational flexibility needed by commercial SOEs to compete in global markets. The current PFMA procurement regime — requiring 3+ quotes, ministerial approvals above thresholds, and B-BBEE scorecards — was designed for the public sector and creates decision-making delays of 6–18 months for major capital investments. SOEs competing in commodity markets (Eskom, Transnet, Denel) and those undertaking large infrastructure projects (PRASA, SANRAL) require a ring-fenced procurement framework that preserves accountability while enabling commercial speed. The reform will also address the B-BBEE compliance burden on specialist international suppliers essential to energy and transport infrastructure programmes, by developing a Strategic Supplier designation pathway.',
    '[
      {"step":1,"description":"National Treasury commissions a diagnostic review of PFMA procurement barriers across five major SOEs (Eskom, Transnet, PRASA, SANRAL, Denel); measure average procurement cycle times, ministerial approval bottlenecks, and instances where B-BBEE compliance excluded the only technically capable supplier; complete within 6 months and publish findings","timeline":"Q2–Q4 2025","responsible_party":"National Treasury / DPEM / AGSA"},
      {"step":2,"description":"Develop the SOE Commercial Procurement Framework: National Treasury drafts a Schedule 3 SOE-specific Treasury Regulation Module under PFMA Section 76(4)(g); provisions to include: (a) delegated authority thresholds for commercial SOEs increased 10x from current levels; (b) 60-day maximum decision cycle for contracts above threshold; (c) emergency procurement provisions for operational continuity; gazette for public comment","timeline":"Q1–Q3 2026","responsible_party":"National Treasury / DPEM"},
      {"step":3,"description":"Strategic Supplier designation pathway for B-BBEE: dtic (BBBEE Commission) develops a Strategic Infrastructure Supplier designation for international OEMs and specialist firms supplying unique technology to SOEs; designated suppliers receive a B-BBEE compliance dispensation for direct procurement but must demonstrate a local supplier development commitment (minimum 30% of contract value in local content or skills transfer within 5 years)","timeline":"Q2–Q4 2026","responsible_party":"dtic / B-BBEE Commission / National Treasury"},
      {"step":4,"description":"Ministerial approval threshold reform: PFMA amendment to increase the Schedule 3A/3B ministerial approval threshold for capital expenditure from current levels to R500 million for commercial SOEs (Eskom, Transnet, SANRAL) and to R100 million for developmental SOEs; delegate approvals above threshold to Accounting Officer with Board audit committee concurrence","timeline":"Q3 2026–Q2 2027","responsible_party":"National Treasury / DPEM / Parliament"},
      {"step":5,"description":"SOE Procurement Performance Dashboard: National Treasury and the Auditor-General co-publish a quarterly SOE Procurement Performance Report tracking average procurement cycle time, B-BBEE compliance rates, emergency procurement use, and contract dispute rates; use as an accountability mechanism and evidence base for further regulatory adjustments","timeline":"Quarterly from Q1 2027","responsible_party":"National Treasury / Auditor-General / DPEM"},
      {"step":6,"description":"Nedlac consultation on B-BBEE framework amendments: table the Strategic Supplier designation and B-BBEE dispensation proposals at Nedlac for business, labour, and community consultation; address concerns about local content displacement; build consensus before enacting B-BBEE Code amendments","timeline":"Q3 2026–Q1 2027","responsible_party":"dtic / Nedlac / B-BBEE Commission"}
    ]',
    '2025 diagnostic; 2026 framework drafting; 2027 implementation; B-BBEE Strategic Supplier designation operational Q4 2026',
    'Diagnostic review: R15–20 million (consulting); Framework development: R10 million (National Treasury internal); B-BBEE Commission Strategic Supplier programme: R5 million setup; net fiscal impact is positive — faster procurement reduces project overruns and financing costs across the SOE portfolio',
    'Public Finance Management Act 1 of 1999 (Section 76 Treasury Regulations amendment; Schedule 3 threshold adjustments); Broad-Based Black Economic Empowerment Act 53 of 2003 (B-BBEE Code amendments for Strategic Supplier designation); Preferential Procurement Policy Framework Act 5 of 2000 (dispensation for strategic procurement)',
    'Most reforms can be implemented through Treasury Regulation amendments (Section 76(4) PFMA) published in the Government Gazette — no parliamentary process for the core procurement flexibility measures. Ministerial approval threshold changes require a PFMA Schedule amendment — tabled as a short amendment bill. B-BBEE Code amendments require a Gazette notice under the BBBEE Act (Minister of dtic) and a 6-month comment period. PPPFA amendments require a statutory instrument published by National Treasury.',
    'Moderate feasibility. National Treasury and DPEM are aligned on the diagnosis. The DA strongly supports SOE procurement liberalisation. The ANC''s B-BBEE constituency will resist any dilution of the empowerment scorecard — the Strategic Supplier designation is designed as a narrow, auditable pathway rather than a general dispensation. Organised labour (COSATU) is concerned about import displacement. Key risk is perception of the reform as an anti-transformation measure — requires careful political communication emphasising infrastructure delivery and local supplier development obligations.',
    'Singapore''s GLC (Government-Linked Company) procurement framework allows Temasek-linked companies to operate under commercial procurement rules while maintaining transparency via annual accountability reviews — the governance model SA''s commercial SOEs should approximate. Chile''s Codelco (state copper company) operates under a separate statutory procurement framework distinct from the public service regime — enabling commercially competitive procurement while maintaining accountability through the Comptroller General. UK''s Crown Commercial Service framework for large infrastructure projects (HS2, Thames Tideway) includes Strategic Supplier provisions with local content obligations — a direct model for SA''s approach.'
);

-- ── ID 61: Eskom Debt Relief Conditions and Restructuring Framework ───────────────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    61,
    'National Treasury will implement the monitoring and enforcement framework for the R254 billion Eskom debt relief package announced in Budget 2023 and structured over three years (FY2023/24–FY2025/26). The relief is conditional on Eskom meeting operational performance milestones linked to load shedding reduction, transmission loss improvements, cost-of-supply tariff alignment, and the restructuring timeline for NTCSA and EGC. NERSA will verify performance against the milestones quarterly; National Treasury will withhold tranches if milestones are not met. The framework must also address Eskom''s remaining R70 billion commercial bank debt not covered by the relief package and the trajectory toward NERSA-approved tariffs that cover the cost of supply. The target is Eskom achieving financial sustainability (no further state support required) by FY2027/28.',
    '[
      {"step":1,"description":"Publish the Eskom Debt Relief Conditions Framework as a formal agreement between National Treasury, DMRE, and Eskom Holdings; define all milestone metrics with precise measurement methodologies — load shedding hours, distribution losses (%), tariff cost-recovery ratio, NTCSA licensing date, EGC hive-down date; make the framework public and table in Parliament","timeline":"Q1 2025 (framework already in operation; formalise public reporting)","responsible_party":"National Treasury / DMRE / Eskom"},
      {"step":2,"description":"NERSA quarterly milestone verification: NERSA publishes a Quarterly Eskom Performance Verification Report assessing each metric against the agreed milestones; include independent technical verification for generation availability (EAF), distribution losses, and tariff revenue-vs-cost analysis; submit to National Treasury, Parliament, and publish on NERSA website","timeline":"Quarterly from Q1 2025","responsible_party":"NERSA / Eskom / National Treasury"},
      {"step":3,"description":"Tariff path implementation: NERSA approves a 5-year tariff determination for Eskom aligned to the cost-of-supply trajectory (target: tariffs covering full operating costs by FY2026/27 and capital cost contribution by FY2028/29); manage distributional impacts through the Lifeline Tariff Block for low-income households (below 350 kWh/month)","timeline":"FY2025/26 MYPD 6 application; determination Q2 2025","responsible_party":"NERSA / Eskom / National Treasury"},
      {"step":4,"description":"Eskom''s remaining commercial debt: National Treasury and Eskom negotiate a restructuring of R70 billion commercial bank debt (Standard Bank, Absa, FirstRand, Investec) not covered by the government relief package; explore conversion to long-term infrastructure bonds; engage DFIs (DBSA, NDB) for refinancing at lower rates; target average debt cost reduction of 150 basis points","timeline":"Q2–Q4 2025","responsible_party":"National Treasury / Eskom Treasury / Commercial banks / DBSA"},
      {"step":5,"description":"Operational efficiency milestones enforcement: National Treasury withholds the final debt relief tranche (FY2025/26) if Eskom fails to achieve: (a) load shedding below Stage 2 average for FY2025/26; (b) distribution losses below 10%; (c) NTCSA licensing completed; (d) EAF above 65%; publish a formal Milestone Assessment Report 6 months before the final tranche decision","timeline":"Q3 2025 (milestone assessment for FY2025/26 tranche)","responsible_party":"National Treasury / NERSA / Presidency (PIIO)"},
      {"step":6,"description":"FY2027/28 Financial Sustainability Assessment: National Treasury and Eskom publish a comprehensive financial model demonstrating Eskom''s path to sustainability without further state support; include sensitivity analysis for tariff scenarios, demand growth projections, and capital expenditure requirements; submit to Parliament for Portfolio Committee oversight","timeline":"Q2 2027","responsible_party":"National Treasury / Eskom / NERSA"}
    ]',
    'Debt relief tranches FY2023/24–FY2025/26; financial sustainability target FY2027/28; tariff cost-recovery by FY2028/29',
    'R254 billion government debt assumption (already approved); R70 billion commercial debt restructuring (Eskom liability, not government); NERSA regulatory capacity increase: R20 million; National Treasury monitoring unit: R15 million; net fiscal risk: contingent liability if Eskom fails milestones and requires additional support',
    'Public Finance Management Act 1 of 1999 (National Treasury debt assumption instruments); Electricity Regulation Act 4 of 2006 (NERSA tariff determination mandate); Medium Term Budget Policy Statement 2022 (Parliamentary approval basis for debt relief); Eskom Holdings SOC Ltd Act (if required for balance sheet restructuring)',
    'The R254 billion debt relief was approved through the 2023 Budget process (Appropriation Act and MTEF allocation) — parliamentary approval already obtained. NERSA tariff determinations are made under the ERA Section 15 and 16 — administrative process requiring no legislation. Commercial bank debt restructuring is a contractual negotiation. Any further government support beyond the approved R254 billion would require new Parliamentary appropriation.',
    'Strong feasibility within the constrained fiscal space. National Treasury has publicly committed to the milestone-conditioned framework. NERSA''s independence is critical — political pressure to approve below-cost tariffs risks undermining financial sustainability. The DA supports strict milestone enforcement; ANC structures are sensitive to electricity tariff increases affecting low-income households. The Lifeline Tariff Block is the political cushion. Eskom management has incentive alignment through performance bonuses linked to EAF and load shedding targets.',
    'Brazil''s Eletrobras financial restructuring (2006–2010) involved a Federal Government R$15 billion debt assumption conditional on operational efficiency milestones monitored by ANEEL (regulator) — the direct model for SA''s framework. The UK''s Railtrack restructuring (2002) transferred £9 billion in debt to the government-owned Network Rail under a performance monitoring framework administered by ORR (Office of Rail and Road). Ireland''s ESB (Electricity Supply Board) 2014 restructuring included a government capital injection conditioned on a 5-year tariff path to cost-recovery — another close precedent.'
);

-- ── ID 62: National Transmission Company Capitalisation and Grid Expansion ────────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    62,
    'NTCSA, National Treasury, and DMRE will implement the R100 billion 5-year grid expansion programme required to connect renewable energy capacity from the Renewable Energy Development Zones (REDZs) in the Northern Cape, Eastern Cape, and Western Cape. Current grid constraints limit renewable energy dispatch by an estimated 8–12%, representing 1,200–1,800 MW of stranded generation capacity. The programme is funded through a blended finance structure: World Bank (IBRD) loans, DBSA project finance, NDB infrastructure bonds, and a government guarantee for NTCSA bonds. The Just Energy Transition Investment Plan (JET-IP) provides the overarching framework. NERSA will regulate NTCSA''s allowed revenue (including return on the capital base) through the Transmission Use of System (TUoS) charge. Grid expansion is the binding constraint on reaching the 18,000 MW of new renewable energy in the IRP 2024.',
    '[
      {"step":1,"description":"NTCSA receives its NERSA transmission licence and publishes the first Annual Transmission Development Plan (ATDP) identifying all grid expansion projects by corridor, voltage class, and REDZ connection priority; publish cost estimates and financing plan; gazette for public comment","timeline":"Q2–Q3 2025","responsible_party":"NTCSA / NERSA / DMRE"},
      {"step":2,"description":"Blended finance capitalisation: National Treasury, DBSA, and World Bank finalise the NTCSA financing structure — R40 billion World Bank IBRD loan (15-year tenor, government guaranteed), R25 billion DBSA project finance, R20 billion NDB infrastructure bond, R15 billion NTCSA own bonds backed by TUoS revenue; close financing arrangements by Q4 2025","timeline":"Q2–Q4 2025","responsible_party":"National Treasury / NTCSA / World Bank / DBSA / NDB"},
      {"step":3,"description":"Renewable Energy Development Zone transmission corridors: NTCSA commences construction on 5 priority REDZ transmission corridors identified in the ATDP — Karoo (Northern Cape), Overberg (Western Cape), Wild Coast (Eastern Cape), Limpopo, and KwaZulu-Natal; complete feasibility studies and EIA processes within 18 months; award construction contracts for first three corridors by Q2 2026","timeline":"Q3 2025–Q4 2027","responsible_party":"NTCSA / DMRE / Environmental Affairs"},
      {"step":4,"description":"Transmission capacity procurement mechanism: NTCSA establishes a Transmission Development Permit (TDP) process for IPPs requiring grid connection; publish connection queue management rules; set a maximum 18-month grid connection timeline for projects within REDZ areas from application to energisation; track against quarterly milestones","timeline":"Q1 2026 (ongoing)","responsible_party":"NTCSA / NERSA / IPP Office"},
      {"step":5,"description":"NERSA Transmission Use of System tariff review: NERSA conducts a full MYPD-equivalent multi-year review of NTCSA''s allowed revenue, incorporating the R100 billion capital programme; establish a Regulatory Asset Base (RAB) model for NTCSA to ensure full cost recovery over the asset life; publish draft tariff methodology for public comment","timeline":"Q3 2025–Q2 2026","responsible_party":"NERSA / NTCSA / National Treasury"},
      {"step":6,"description":"Interconnector expansion to neighbouring countries: NTCSA, SAPP (Southern African Power Pool), and ESKOM negotiate an expansion of cross-border interconnectors — increasing SA-Mozambique (HCB hydro), SA-Namibia, and SA-Zimbabwe capacity by 2,000 MW total; reduces the variable renewable energy curtailment problem and supports regional power pooling under the SADC Energy Protocol","timeline":"Q2 2026–Q4 2029","responsible_party":"NTCSA / SAPP / DMRE / DIRCO"},
      {"step":7,"description":"JET-IP quarterly progress reporting: NTCSA and National Treasury publish quarterly grid expansion progress reports under the JET-IP monitoring framework; include MW of new transmission capacity energised, grid connection queue metrics, blended finance drawdowns, and REDZ corridor construction status; report to the Presidential Climate Commission","timeline":"Quarterly from Q3 2025","responsible_party":"National Treasury / NTCSA / Presidential Climate Commission"}
    ]',
    '2025–2030; NTCSA licence Q3 2025; financing closed Q4 2025; first REDZ corridors energised Q4 2027; full R100 billion programme by 2030',
    'R100 billion over 5 years: R40 billion World Bank (government guaranteed), R25 billion DBSA, R20 billion NDB bonds, R15 billion NTCSA own bonds backed by TUoS revenue; government contingent liability on guarantees: R40 billion (not on-balance-sheet unless called)',
    'Electricity Regulation Amendment Act (2024) — NTCSA licensing and transmission market framework; National Energy Regulator of South Africa Act 40 of 2004 (NERSA tariff determination); Development Bank of Southern Africa Act 13 of 1997 (DBSA financing instruments); Government guarantee instruments under PFMA Section 70',
    'NTCSA''s NERSA transmission licence is granted under the ERA — administrative process. The government guarantees for NTCSA bonds and World Bank loans require National Treasury approval under PFMA Section 70 — a Cabinet-approved guarantee (not parliamentary vote required for guarantees below statutory limit). REDZ Environmental Impact Assessments are processed under NEMA. Cross-border interconnector agreements are executive DIRCO instruments under the SADC Energy Protocol — no domestic legislation required.',
    'Strong feasibility. Grid expansion has broad political and business support. World Bank, DBSA, and NDB have publicly indicated financing commitments. The Presidential Climate Commission supports REDZ development. Environmental NGOs generally support renewable energy grid expansion. Key implementation risk is environmental approvals (EIA timelines for transmission lines), land access disputes in Northern Cape and Eastern Cape, and procurement capacity within the newly established NTCSA. Operational Vulindlela tracks grid expansion as a top reform priority.',
    'Morocco''s ONEE (Office National de l''Electricité et de l''Eau Potable) grid expansion programme connected 4,000 MW of renewables (Noor CSP, Ouarzazate, Midelt) through a World Bank and AfDB blended finance structure — the closest comparable project in Africa. Germany''s Energiewende grid expansion programme (Netzausbau) required €100 billion in transmission investment coordinated by the Federal Network Agency (Bundesnetzagentur) — the regulatory model for NERSA''s NTCSA RAB methodology. Chile''s HVDC transmission line programme connecting the Atacama renewable zone to Santiago used blended DFI finance and reduced curtailment from 15% to under 3%.'
);

-- ── ID 63: Denel Strategic Equity Partner and Defence Industrial Viability ────────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    63,
    'DPEM and National Treasury will implement a Strategic Equity Partner (SEP) programme for Denel to secure a minority stake purchase (25–35%) by a global defence OEM, recapitalise the balance sheet, and restore operational viability for Denel''s strategically important product lines. Denel is technically insolvent with R3.4 billion in accumulated debt and R18 billion in legacy liabilities (pension obligations and government-guaranteed debt). The government has provided R5 billion in debt relief since 2020 without a credible turnaround. The SEP programme must protect ITAR-sensitive technology, preserve the Landward Systems (Rooivalk attack helicopter, G5/G6 artillery), Optronics, and Denel Dynamics (missile systems) capabilities while making the organisation commercially viable. A parallel Denel rationalisation will close non-viable divisions (Overberg Test Range operations can be concessioned) and focus on the 3–4 product lines with genuine export value.',
    '[
      {"step":1,"description":"DPEM commissions an independent strategic and financial review of Denel: assess the commercial viability and export potential of each division (Landward Systems, Denel Dynamics, Optronics, PMP, Denel Aerostructures); identify which divisions are commercially viable with SEP investment and which should be wound down or concessioned; identify potential SEP candidates (Airbus Defence, Rheinmetall, BAE Systems, Rafael Advanced Defense Systems); complete within 6 months","timeline":"Q2–Q4 2025","responsible_party":"DPEM / National Treasury / ARMSCOR"},
      {"step":2,"description":"ITAR and technology protection framework: DPEM and DIRCO coordinate with the US State Department (DDTC) and domestic defence technology classification authorities (ARMSCOR) to establish a clear technology transfer protection protocol for the SEP transaction; define carve-outs for ITAR-controlled items; ensure SEP agreement includes security-cleared director requirements and technology access controls","timeline":"Q3 2025–Q1 2026","responsible_party":"DPEM / DIRCO / ARMSCOR / State Attorney"},
      {"step":3,"description":"SEP transaction process: DPEM appoints a specialist defence transaction advisor (subject to PFMA competitive appointment); issue Request for Proposals to qualified global defence OEMs; structure a 25–35% minority stake sale through a competitive process with a 10-year operational partnership agreement covering technology transfer, export marketing, and capability development obligations","timeline":"Q1–Q4 2026","responsible_party":"DPEM / National Treasury / ARMSCOR"},
      {"step":4,"description":"Denel rationalisation: close or concession non-viable divisions identified in the strategic review; negotiate pension liability settlement with the Denel Pension Fund and National Treasury; implement a voluntary separation package for redundant employees funded by the R5 billion restructuring provision; protect collective bargaining rights through Nedlac consultation with UASA and Solidarity","timeline":"Q2 2026–Q4 2027","responsible_party":"DPEM / Denel Board / National Treasury / Nedlac"},
      {"step":5,"description":"Export programme for viable product lines: ARMSCOR and DIRCO develop a dedicated export facilitation programme for Denel Landward Systems and Dynamics products in target markets (African Union peacekeeping, Middle East, South America); appoint defence attaches in 5 priority markets; establish a government-to-government arms sales framework under the National Conventional Arms Control Act","timeline":"Q3 2026–Q4 2028","responsible_party":"ARMSCOR / DIRCO / DPEM / NCACC"},
      {"step":6,"description":"Post-SEP performance monitoring: DPEM and National Treasury agree on a 5-year performance framework with the SEP covering employment targets, technology milestones, and export revenue objectives; publish an annual Denel Performance Report; table in Parliament; require ARMSCOR Annual Report to include Denel capability assessment","timeline":"Annual from Q4 2027","responsible_party":"DPEM / Denel Board / ARMSCOR / Parliament"}
    ]',
    'Strategic review Q4 2025; SEP transaction Q4 2026; rationalisation complete Q4 2027; operational viability target FY2028/29',
    'Government debt relief already approved: R5 billion (operational costs 2020–2024); SEP transaction advisory: R80–100 million; pension liability settlement: R4–6 billion (contingent, government-guaranteed); Denel rationalisation separation packages: R1–1.5 billion; net positive fiscal impact if SEP investment of R2–3 billion is secured from private partner',
    'Defence Act 42 of 2002 (Denel mandate and ARMSCOR relationship); National Conventional Arms Control Act 41 of 2002 (export control framework); Companies Act 71 of 2008 (Denel Holdings corporate restructuring); PFMA Schedule 2 (Major Public Entity status); Armaments Corporation of South Africa Limited Act 51 of 2003',
    'SEP minority stake sale is a share sale transaction authorised by DPEM ministerial determination and Cabinet approval — no primary legislation required, though the Denel Act may need amendment if the state is no longer the sole shareholder. Technology export framework operates under the NCACC Act — no legislative change required. Pension liability settlement requires National Treasury approval under PFMA Section 72. Defence procurement aligned to ARMSCOR Act procedures.',
    'Low-to-moderate feasibility. DPEM has acknowledged Denel''s insolvency and the need for a SEP. National Treasury support is conditional on a credible restructuring plan. The DA and IFP support a market-based restructuring. ANC defence-industrial policy community is divided — some support SEP, others resist any private ownership of strategic defence assets. Labour unions (UASA, Solidarity) representing Denel workers support restructuring if retrenchment is managed. The technology protection framework is a critical diplomatic prerequisite.',
    'Sweden''s SAAB privatisation (1990s) from a state-owned defence conglomerate to a publicly listed company with a government golden share retained oversight while enabling commercial flexibility — a comparable governance model. Turkey''s ASELSAN and Roketsan public-private partnership model with OYAK (military pension fund as anchor shareholder) demonstrates how a mid-income country can build a sustainable defence industrial base through structured private participation. India''s HAL (Hindustan Aeronautics Limited) Strategic Partnership Policy (2016) invited private defence OEMs (Airbus, Boeing, Lockheed Martin) to take minority stakes in licensed production entities — directly comparable to SA''s Rooivalk and G6 export strategy.'
);

-- ── ID 64: Alexkor and Safcol Land Claims — Long-Delayed Resolution ───────────────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    64,
    'The DPEM, DRDLR (Department of Agriculture, Land Reform and Rural Development), and National Treasury will implement the long-delayed settlement of land claims against Alexkor (Richtersveld community, Northern Cape) and Safcol (multiple claimants in Mpumalanga and Limpopo). The Richtersveld-Alexkor claim was adjudicated by the Constitutional Court in 2003 (Alexkor Ltd v Richtersveld Community), establishing the community''s rights, but implementation has stalled for 15+ years. The Pooling and Sharing Joint Venture (PSJV) between Alexkor and the Richtersveld community was established but has not delivered promised benefits. Safcol''s Mpumalanga Forestry (Komatiland Forests) faces overlapping land claims from multiple communities that have frozen the strategic sale of a minority stake for more than a decade. Resolution requires clear legislative instruments, a structured benefit-sharing mechanism, and a development investment plan for the Richtersveld.',
    '[
      {"step":1,"description":"DPEM and DRDLR convene a Richtersveld Settlement Implementation Task Team with representation from Alexkor, the Richtersveld Community Property Association (CPA), National Treasury, and the Land Claims Court; conduct a comprehensive audit of the PSJV''s financial performance and benefit-sharing obligations since 2007; publish audit findings within 6 months","timeline":"Q2–Q4 2025","responsible_party":"DPEM / DRDLR / Land Claims Court"},
      {"step":2,"description":"Alexkor-Richtersveld PSJV restructuring: negotiate a revised PSJV agreement with the Richtersveld CPA that: (a) increases the community''s share of diamond mining proceeds from current levels to minimum 30%; (b) establishes a Richtersveld Development Trust with a dedicated R500 million capitalisation for infrastructure (water, roads, housing, broadband) in the Richtersveld; (c) provides the community with representation on Alexkor''s Board; require agreement ratification by the Richtersveld CPA in a community meeting","timeline":"Q1–Q3 2026","responsible_party":"DPEM / Alexkor Board / Richtersveld CPA"},
      {"step":3,"description":"Safcol land claims mapping and negotiation: DRDLR commissions a comprehensive cadastral mapping of all outstanding land claims overlapping Safcol-managed state forestry areas in Mpumalanga (Komatiland Forests, Hans Merensky) and Limpopo (Letaba); establish a Land Claims Mediation Panel for each claim with Land Claims Court oversight; set a maximum 24-month resolution timeline per claim","timeline":"Q2 2025–Q4 2027","responsible_party":"DRDLR / Land Claims Court / Safcol"},
      {"step":4,"description":"Safcol strategic minority stake sale: once the primary land claims are resolved or structured into benefit-sharing agreements, DPEM proceeds with a competitive sale of 30–40% of Safcol to a strategic timber industry partner with a B-BBEE component; reinvest proceeds into the community benefit-sharing trusts and Safcol forestry infrastructure","timeline":"Q1–Q4 2028 (conditional on claim resolution)","responsible_party":"DPEM / National Treasury / Safcol Board"},
      {"step":5,"description":"Legislative instruments for claim settlement: DRDLR drafts a short Restitution of Land Rights Amendment Bill to provide a clear statutory basis for the structured benefit-sharing mechanism as an alternative to direct land transfer (to preserve operating asset integrity); include provisions for community oversight boards and mandatory annual financial disclosure","timeline":"Q2 2026–Q2 2027","responsible_party":"DRDLR / Department of Justice / Parliament"},
      {"step":6,"description":"Richtersveld Development Investment Plan: DPEM and COGTA co-develop a 10-year Richtersveld Development Investment Plan leveraging the Development Trust proceeds; focus on water infrastructure (Orange River scheme extension), sustainable mining beyond diamonds (rare earths potential), eco-tourism, and community solar energy; secure DBSA and IDC co-financing","timeline":"Q4 2026–Q4 2027","responsible_party":"DPEM / COGTA / DBSA / IDC / Richtersveld CPA"}
    ]',
    '2025–2026 audit and PSJV restructuring; Safcol claims resolution 2025–2028; Safcol minority stake sale 2028; Richtersveld Development Plan 2027',
    'Richtersveld Development Trust capitalisation: R500 million (Alexkor mining proceeds and government contribution); Safcol land claims mediation: R30–50 million (DRDLR legal and survey costs); Safcol strategic sale: expected R1.5–2.5 billion in proceeds; Restitution Amendment Bill: negligible legislative cost; overall net positive for fiscus if Safcol sale proceeds',
    'Restitution of Land Rights Act 22 of 1994 (Restitution Amendment Bill required); Land Reform (Labour Tenants) Act 3 of 1996; Companies Act 71 of 2008 (PSJV restructuring); PFMA Schedule 2 (Alexkor and Safcol as major public entities); Communal Property Associations Act 28 of 1996 (Richtersveld CPA governance)',
    'A Restitution of Land Rights Amendment Bill is required to provide a statutory benefit-sharing mechanism as an alternative to direct land transfer — to be introduced in Parliament by DRDLR. This is a politically sensitive but well-precedented legislative instrument (similar to the 2014 Amendment Bill). The PSJV restructuring agreement is a contractual instrument requiring Board and CPA ratification. Alexkor and Safcol corporate restructuring operates under the Companies Act. Ministerial approval (DPEM) required for the Safcol stake sale under PFMA Schedule 2.',
    'Low-moderate feasibility. The constitutional and legal basis for settlement is established (Alexkor CC 2003 judgment). The political will to implement has been the missing ingredient. The GNU''s rural development constituency (ANC, PAC-aligned structures) supports resolution; the DA supports commercial viability restoration of both SOEs. Key risks: Richtersveld CPA internal governance disputes; multiple overlapping Safcol claimants with conflicting demands; National Treasury resistance to Richtersveld Trust capitalisation from government budget rather than mining proceeds.',
    'Canada''s comprehensive land claims settlements with First Nations under the Comprehensive Claims Policy (1973, revised 1986) demonstrate the viability of benefit-sharing and co-management models as alternatives to full land transfer for operating resource extraction assets. Namibia''s communal land reform programme implemented after independence used community conservancy trusts with direct revenue-sharing from wildlife tourism and mining — a precedent for the Richtersveld Development Trust model. Australia''s Native Title Act (1993) and Ranger Uranium Agreement with the Kakadu community provide a structured royalty and co-management framework for resource extraction on land with indigenous title — directly comparable to the Alexkor diamond mining situation.'
);

-- ── ID 65: SAA Successor Entity — Commercial Viability Without Ongoing State Bail-outs ─
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    65,
    'DPEM and National Treasury will finalise the Takatso Consortium equity transaction (49% stake), implement SAA''s commercial viability plan, and establish a clear milestone framework for achieving financial independence by FY2027/28. SAA emerged from business rescue in 2021 after the government spent R32 billion in bail-outs over 2017–2021. The new entity operates with approximately R10 billion in equity from Takatso, but requires route rationalisation, fleet modernisation through wet lease arrangements, IATA IOSA recertification, and operational discipline to become sustainable. The government''s 51% stake must be managed actively — including the option of further stake reduction to a minority position if commercial viability requires it. No further unplanned government capital injections are acceptable within the GNU''s fiscal consolidation framework.',
    '[
      {"step":1,"description":"Finalise the Takatso Consortium transaction: DPEM and SAA Board complete the delayed 49% stake transfer to Takatso (Global Aviation and ENsource); obtain all regulatory approvals (Competition Commission, SACAA); finalise shareholder agreement with clear governance provisions, Takatso capital injection schedule, and route development commitments; set longstop date of Q2 2025","timeline":"Q1–Q2 2025 (overdue)","responsible_party":"DPEM / SAA Board / Competition Commission / Takatso"},
      {"step":2,"description":"Commercial viability plan publication: SAA Board and Takatso co-publish a 5-year Commercial Viability Plan (2025–2030) covering: (a) network rationalisation to 25 routes with minimum 70% load factors; (b) fleet plan based on wet lease (short-term) transitioning to owned aircraft by 2028; (c) revenue targets by route; (d) cost reduction milestones including labour productivity metrics; publish in the Government Gazette and table in Parliament","timeline":"Q2 2025","responsible_party":"SAA Board / Takatso / DPEM"},
      {"step":3,"description":"IATA IOSA recertification: SAA appoints a designated IOSA Audit Organisation to conduct the safety and operational standards audit; address all findings within 90 days; obtain IOSA recertification by Q3 2025; IOSA certification is a prerequisite for codeshare agreements with major alliance carriers (Star Alliance codeshares are a revenue multiplier)","timeline":"Q2–Q3 2025","responsible_party":"SAA / SACAA / IATA"},
      {"step":4,"description":"Wet lease fleet rationalisation: SAA negotiates wet lease agreements (aircraft + crew) with 2–3 major carriers (Ethiopian Airlines, Turkish Airlines, Emirates) for initial fleet; limit wet lease cost exposure to below 25% of total seat capacity; develop a 5-year plan to transition to owned or long-term dry-leased narrowbody fleet (Airbus A320neo or Boeing 737 MAX) as creditworthiness improves","timeline":"Q2 2025–Q4 2026","responsible_party":"SAA / Takatso"},
      {"step":5,"description":"No further state bail-out commitment: DPEM and National Treasury publish a joint Policy Statement confirming that no further unplanned capital injections will be provided to SAA beyond the approved business rescue exit equity; establish a Financial Distress Protocol that triggers DPEM intervention and potential stake reduction (to below 50%) rather than bail-out if SAA fails to meet Commercial Viability Plan milestones","timeline":"Q2 2025","responsible_party":"National Treasury / DPEM"},
      {"step":6,"description":"Annual SAA Performance Review: SAA Board tables an annual performance review against the Commercial Viability Plan milestones at a public Parliament Portfolio Committee on Public Enterprises hearing; include load factors, yield per passenger km, EBITDA margin, debt service coverage ratio, and employment data; Competition Commission monitors any route monopoly behaviour","timeline":"Annual from Q4 2025","responsible_party":"SAA Board / DPEM / Parliament / Competition Commission"},
      {"step":7,"description":"Government stake reduction pathway: National Treasury and DPEM develop a 3-year pathway for reducing the government''s SAA stake from 51% to 26% (strategic minority) through a further share sale — either to a global airline partner, black institutional investors, or a public offering — conditional on SAA achieving 2 consecutive years of EBITDA profitability; proceed only with Cabinet approval","timeline":"Q3 2027–Q4 2028 (conditional)","responsible_party":"DPEM / National Treasury / Takatso / SAA Board"}
    ]',
    'Takatso transaction finalised Q2 2025; IOSA recertification Q3 2025; Commercial Viability Plan 2025–2030; EBITDA break-even target FY2026/27; financial independence FY2027/28',
    'Government equity already committed through business rescue exit (R10 billion post-rescue equity base); Takatso capital injection: R3–5 billion (Takatso obligation); government operating support: zero beyond approved equity — hard constraint; stake reduction proceeds (conditional): R2–4 billion; SACAA and DPEM oversight: R20 million per year',
    'Companies Act 71 of 2008 (SAA governance and shareholder agreement); Civil Aviation Act 13 of 2009 (SACAA licensing and IOSA framework); Competition Act 89 of 1998 (Competition Commission approval for Takatso transaction); PFMA Schedule 2 (DPEM oversight of SAA as major public entity); Air Services Licensing Act 115 of 1990',
    'The Takatso transaction requires Competition Commission approval (application submitted) — administrative process under the Competition Act. SAA remains a Schedule 2 PFMA entity until shareholding changes — no legislative amendment required for current structure. Reducing government stake below 50% may require a National Assembly resolution under PFMA Schedule provisions. Wet lease agreements and route licences operate under the Air Services Licensing Act — SACAA administrative approval. No primary legislation required for the core commercial viability programme.',
    'Moderate feasibility, contingent on Takatso fulfilling investment commitments. The GNU has drawn a politically credible red line on further bail-outs. National Treasury and the DA are firm. ANC''s labour constituency and the South African Cabin Crew Association (SACCA) resist headcount reductions. Key risk is the Takatso transaction collapsing due to due diligence concerns — a contingency plan involving an alternative investor process or a managed wind-down must be prepared. The "no further bail-out" commitment is the most important governance signal for market credibility.',
    'Kenya Airways''s strategic partnership with Air France-KLM and KQ''s partial privatisation model (government retains minority stake after initial privatisation reversed) illustrates the political difficulty of full flag-carrier privatisation in an African context — and the utility of a strategic partner model. Ethiopian Airlines''s self-funded commercial expansion from a government-owned airline to Africa''s largest carrier demonstrates that state ownership need not preclude commercial discipline — but requires management autonomy from political interference that SAA has historically lacked. Singapore Airlines'' complete commercial independence despite being government-owned (via Temasek) is the aspirational benchmark for what SAA could achieve under the Takatso model if governance is maintained.'
);

COMMIT;
